---
import ExternalLink from '../../components/ExternalLink.astro';
import PageLayout from '../../layouts/PageLayout.astro';
---

<PageLayout
  title="Links"
  description="External resources related to Free Ham Radio Curriculum and amateur radio."
>
  <div class="content-sections">
    <h1>Links</h1>
    <p>External sites only. For pages on this site, use the navigation above.</p>

    <section>
      <h2>Related organizations</h2>
      <ul>
        <li>
          <ExternalLink href="https://www.ampr.org/">ARDC</ExternalLink> — Amateur Radio Digital
          Communications — a foundation that invests in open technology, education, and infra to advance
          amateur radio worldwide.
        </li>
        <li>
          <ExternalLink href="https://www.arrl.org/">ARRL</ExternalLink> — The original national
          association for amateur radio in the U.S.
        </li>
      </ul>
    </section>

    <section>
      <h2>Source code</h2>
      <ul>
        <li>
          <ExternalLink href="https://github.com/">GitHub</ExternalLink> — curriculum source (placeholder
          URL)
        </li>
      </ul>
    </section>

    <section>
      <h2>Emergency preparedness</h2>
      <ul>
        <li>
          <ExternalLink href="https://www.arrl.org/ares">ARRL ARES</ExternalLink> — Amateur Radio
          Emergency Service volunteer program for public-service communications.
        </li>
        <li>
          <ExternalLink href="https://www.weather.gov/nwr">NOAA Weather Radio</ExternalLink> —
          Nationwide network of weather broadcasts you can monitor before you transmit.
        </li>
        <li>
          <ExternalLink href="https://www.ready.gov/communications">Ready.gov</ExternalLink> — U.S.
          government guidance on staying informed during emergencies.
        </li>
      </ul>

      <h3>PACE planning</h3>
      <ul>
        <li>
          <ExternalLink
            href="https://www.cisa.gov/sites/default/files/2024-10/2024_NCSWICPTE_Leveraging_PACE_Plan_Emergency_Comms_Ecosystems.pdf"
            >Leveraging PACE Plans</ExternalLink
          > — U.S. government guide to Primary, Alternate, Contingency, and Emergency comms for disaster
          response.
        </li>
        <li>
          <ExternalLink href="https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/PACE_(communication_methodology)"
            >Wikipedia — PACE</ExternalLink
          > — Background on the PACE framework and how military and emergency planners use it.
        </li>
        <li>
          <ExternalLink
            href="https://fortunefavorstheprepared.com/preparedness-book-of-knowledge-2/communications/comms-p-a-c-e/"
            >Fortune Favors the Prepared</ExternalLink
          > — Civilian examples of building a four-tier communications plan for grid-down scenarios.
        </li>
        <li>
          <ExternalLink
            href="https://readyradio.com/blogs/radio-fundamentals/prepping-emergency-communications-before-an-emergency"
            >Ready Radio</ExternalLink
          > — Practical advice on layering radio and other backup methods into a PACE plan.
        </li>
      </ul>
    </section>

    <section>
      <h2>Getting a GMRS or Ham license</h2>
      <ul>
        <li>
          <ExternalLink href="https://apps.fcc.gov/cores">FCC CORES</ExternalLink> — Register for a free
          FCC Registration Number (FRN); required before any license application or exam.
        </li>
        <li>
          <ExternalLink
            href="https://www.fcc.gov/wireless/support/universal-licensing-system-uls-resources/getting-fcc-registration-number-frn"
            >FCC — Getting an FRN</ExternalLink
          > — Step-by-step help for first-time FRN registration in CORES.
        </li>
        <li>
          <ExternalLink
            href="https://www.fcc.gov/wireless/bureau-divisions/mobility-division/general-mobile-radio-service-gmrs"
            >FCC — General Mobile Radio Service (GMRS)</ExternalLink
          > — Official overview of GMRS rules, who may license, and ten-year license terms.
        </li>
        <li>
          <ExternalLink href="https://www.arrl.org/find-an-amateur-radio-license-exam-session"
            >ARRL — Find an exam session</ExternalLink
          > — Search for in-person or online amateur radio license exams by location and date.
        </li>
        <li>
          <ExternalLink href="https://www.arrl.org/online-exam-session">ARRL — Online exam sessions</ExternalLink>
          — List of volunteer exam teams that offer remote ham license tests.
        </li>
        <li>
          <ExternalLink href="https://glaarg.org/examinees/">GLAARG</ExternalLink> — Greater Los Angeles
          Amateur Radio Group VEC; widely used for online exam sessions nationwide.
        </li>
        <li>
          <ExternalLink href="https://larc-vec.org/licensing.php">Laurel VEC — Licensing information</ExternalLink>
          — Free in-person amateur radio exams coordinated by volunteer teams across the country.
        </li>
        <li>
          <ExternalLink href="https://www.arrl.org/what-to-bring-to-an-exam-session"
            >ARRL — What to bring to an exam</ExternalLink
          > — Checklist of FRN, ID, and fee requirements before exam day.
        </li>
        <li>
          <ExternalLink href="https://wireless2.fcc.gov/UlsEntry/licManager/login.jsp"
            >FCC ULS License Manager</ExternalLink
          > — Log in with your FRN to apply for a GMRS license or pay the FCC fee after passing a ham exam.
        </li>
      </ul>
    </section>
  </div>
</PageLayout>
